│ THOUGHT: The bug stems from SLP’s FixBoolLogicalOps helper around lines 20340-20360 in SLPVectorizer.cpp. It tries to preserve poison semantics for boolean/select reductions by         │
│ possibly swapping operands or freezing the LHS when both original ops could make both operands be RHS. However, it only freezes LHS. In the provided miscompile, this causes a freeze to │
│ be applied to the condition (%c3) and then the reassociated select uses %c1 (poison) as the selected true-value, making the result poison when originally it wasn’t used. To fix, we     │
│ must avoid increasing poison: if we can’t reorder to keep both operands in safe positions and both could be poison-sensitive, we should freeze both operands that may be used in the     │
│ data position after reassociation (or conservatively avoid freezing only the condition). A minimal safe change is to freeze both LHS and RHS when neither early-return nor swap is       │
│ applicable and they are not guaranteed non-poison, ensuring no data operand introduces new poison.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ applypatch << 'PATCH'                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ *** Begin Patch                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ *** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                                                                                         │
│ @@                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ -        if (LHS != VectorizedTree)                                                                                                                                                      │
│ -          LHS = Builder.CreateFreeze(LHS);                                                                                                                                              │
│ +        // At this point, neither we early-returned nor swapped operands to match                                                                                                       │
│ +        // original poison semantics. Freezing only one side (LHS) may still allow                                                                                                      │
│ +        // the other side (RHS) to be selected as a data operand and introduce                                                                                                          │
│ +        // new poison compared to the original evaluation order. This can make the                                                                                                      │
│ +        // transformed code more poisonous than the source (see Alive2 repro in                                                                                                         │
│ +        // the issue where %c1 stayed un-frozen and was selected).                                                                                                                      │
